,"pos":[1117,1240]},{"content":"That's because XAML is intended to be extensible, that's what the \"X\" in the acronym XAML means.","pos":[1241,1337]},{"content":"Once XAML is parsed, the elements and attributes you reference in XAML are expected to exist in some backing code representation, either in the core types defined by the Windows Runtime, or in types that extend or are based off the Windows Runtime.","pos":[1338,1586]},{"content":"The SDK documentation sometimes refers to the types that are already built-in to the Windows Runtime and can be used in XAML as being the <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>XAML vocabulary<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> for the Windows Runtime.","pos":[1587,1767],"source":" The SDK documentation sometimes refers to the types that are already built-in to the Windows Runtime and can be used in XAML as being the *XAML vocabulary* for the Windows Runtime."},{"content":"Microsoft Visual Studio helps you to produce markup that's valid within this XAML vocabulary.","pos":[1768,1861]},{"content":"Visual Studio can also include your custom types for XAML usage so long as the source of those types is referenced correctly in the project.","pos":[1862,2002]},{"content":"For more info about XAML and custom types, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XAML namespaces and namespace mapping<ept id=\"p1\">](xaml-namespaces-and-namespace-mapping.md)</ept>.","pos":[2003,2132],"source":" For more info about XAML and custom types, see [XAML namespaces and namespace mapping](xaml-namespaces-and-namespace-mapping.md)."},{"content":"Declaring objects","pos":[2138,2155]},{"content":"Programmers often think in terms of objects and members, whereas a markup language is conceptualized as elements and attributes.","pos":[2157,2285]},{"content":"In the most basic sense, an element that you declare in XAML markup becomes an object in a backing runtime object representation.","pos":[2286,2415]},{"content":"To create a run-time object for your app, you declare a XAML element in the XAML markup.","pos":[2416,2504]},{"content":"The object is created when the Windows Runtime loads your XAML.","pos":[2505,2568]},{"content":"A XAML file always has exactly one element serving as its root, which declares an object that will be the conceptual root of some programming structure such as a page, or the object graph of the entire run-time definition of an application.","pos":[2570,2810]},{"content":"In terms of XAML syntax, there are three ways to declare objects in XAML:","pos":[2812,2885]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Directly, using object element syntax:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> This uses opening and closing tags to instantiate an object as an XML-form element.","pos":[2891,3017],"source":"**Directly, using object element syntax:** This uses opening and closing tags to instantiate an object as an XML-form element."},{"content":"You can use this syntax to declare root objects or to create nested objects that set property values.","pos":[3018,3119]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Indirectly, using attribute syntax:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> This uses an inline string value that has instructions for how to create an object.","pos":[3124,3247],"source":"**Indirectly, using attribute syntax:** This uses an inline string value that has instructions for how to create an object."},{"content":"The XAML parser uses this string to set the value of a property to a newly created reference value.","pos":[3248,3347]},{"content":"Support for it is limited to certain common objects and properties.","pos":[3348,3415]},{"content":"Using a markup extension.","pos":[3420,3445]},{"content":"This does not mean that you always have the choice of any syntax for object creation in a XAML vocabulary.","pos":[3447,3553]},{"content":"Some objects can be created only by using object element syntax.","pos":[3554,3618]},{"content":"Some objects can be created only by being initially set in an attribute.","pos":[3619,3691]},{"content":"In fact, objects that can be created with either object element or attribute syntax are comparatively rare in XAML vocabularies.","pos":[3692,3820]},{"content":"Even if both syntax forms are possible, one of the syntaxes will be more common as a matter of style.","pos":[3821,3922]},{"content":"There are also techniques you can use in XAML to reference existing objects rather than creating new values.","pos":[3923,4031],"source":"\nThere are also techniques you can use in XAML to reference existing objects rather than creating new values."},{"content":"The existing objects might be defined either in other areas of XAML, or might exist implicitly through some behavior of the platform and its application or programming models.","pos":[4032,4207]},{"content":"Declaring an object by using object element syntax","pos":[4213,4263]},{"content":"To declare an object with object element syntax, you write tags like this: <ph id=\"ph1\">`&lt;objectName&gt;  &lt;/objectName&gt;`</ph>, where <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>objectName<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> is the type name for the object you want to instantiate.","pos":[4265,4446],"source":"To declare an object with object element syntax, you write tags like this: `<objectName>  </objectName>`, where *objectName* is the type name for the object you want to instantiate."},{"content":"Here's object element usage to declare a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Canvas<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209267)</ept> object:","pos":[4447,4566],"source":" Here's object element usage to declare a [**Canvas**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209267) object:"},{"pos":[4600,4746],"content":"If the object does not contain other objects, you can declare the object element by using one self-closing tag instead of an opening/closing pair:"},{"content":"Containers","pos":[4765,4775]},{"content":"Many objects used as UI elements, such as <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Canvas<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](http