n handling; these features are available in the dependency property system.","pos":[9593,9776]},{"content":"For more info on how dependency properties are useful for calculated property support, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Dependency properties overview<ept id=\"p1\">](dependency-properties-overview.md)</ept>.","pos":[9777,9936],"source":" For more info on how dependency properties are useful for calculated property support, see [Dependency properties overview](dependency-properties-overview.md)."},{"content":"Collection syntax in XAML gives an appearance that you are setting a read-only property, but in fact you are not.","pos":[9938,10051]},{"content":"See \"Setting a Property by Using a Collection Syntax\" section later in this topic.","pos":[10052,10134]},{"content":"Setting a property by using attribute syntax","pos":[10140,10184]},{"content":"Setting an attribute value is the typical means by which you set a property value in a markup language, for example in XML or HTML.","pos":[10186,10317]},{"content":"Setting XAML attributes is similar to how you set attribute values in XML.","pos":[10318,10392]},{"content":"The attribute name is specified at any point within the tags following the element name, separated from element name by at least one whitespace.","pos":[10393,10537]},{"content":"The attribute name is followed by an equals sign.","pos":[10538,10587]},{"content":"The attribute value is contained within a pair of quotes.","pos":[10588,10645]},{"content":"The quotes can be either double quotes or single quotes so long as they match and enclose the value.","pos":[10646,10746]},{"content":"The attribute value itself must be expressible as a string.","pos":[10747,10806]},{"content":"The string often contains numerals, but to XAML, all attribute values are string values until the XAML parser gets involved and does some basic value conversion.","pos":[10807,10968]},{"pos":[10970,11419],"content":"This example uses attribute syntax for four attributes to set the 