:[18676,18889]},{"content":"XAML supports multiple child elements as well as supporting a typical backing collection model by treating properties that use a collection type as implicit, and performing special handling for any child elements of a collection type.","pos":[18890,19124]},{"content":"Many collection properties are also identified as the XAML content property for the class.","pos":[19126,19216]},{"content":"The combination of implicit collection processing and XAML content syntax is frequently seen in types used for control compositing, such as panels, views, or items controls.","pos":[19217,19390]},{"content":"For example, the following examples show the simplest possible XAML for compositing two peer UI elements within a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>StackPanel<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209635)</ept>.","pos":[19391,19580],"source":" For example, the following examples show the simplest possible XAML for compositing two peer UI elements within a [**StackPanel**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209635)."},{"content":"The mechanism of XAML collection syntax","pos":[19827,19866]},{"content":"It might at first appear that XAML is enabling a \"set\" of the read-only collection property.","pos":[19868,19960]},{"content":"In reality, what XAML enables here is adding items to an existing collection.","pos":[19961,20038]},{"content":"The XAML language and XAML processors implementing XAML support rely on a convention in backing collection types to enable this syntax.","pos":[20039,20174]},{"content":"Typically there is a backing property such as an indexer or <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Items<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> property that refers to specific items of the collection.","pos":[20175,20302],"source":" Typically there is a backing property such as an indexer or **Items** property that refers to specific items of the collection."},{"content":"Generally, that property is not