ameter type."},{"content":"For collection properties, be careful about when you try to specify the collection explicitly as an object element.","pos":[21151,21266]},{"content":"A XAML parser will create a new object whenever it encounters an object element.","pos":[21267,21347]},{"content":"If the collection property you're trying to use is read-only, this can throw a XAML parse exception.","pos":[21348,21448]},{"content":"Just use the implicit collection syntax, and you won't see that exception.","pos":[21449,21523]},{"content":"When to use attribute or property element syntax","pos":[21528,21576]},{"content":"All properties that support being set in XAML will support attribute or property element syntax for direct value setting, but potentially will not support either syntax interchangeably.","pos":[21578,21763]},{"content":"Some properties do support either syntax, and some properties support additional syntax options like a XAML content property.","pos":[21764,21889]},{"content":"The type of XAML syntax supported by a property depends on the type of object that the property uses as its property type.","pos":[21890,22012]},{"content":"If the property type is a primitive type, such as a double (float or decimal), integer, Boolean, or string, the property always supports attribute syntax.","pos":[22013,22167]},{"content":"You can also use attribute syntax to set a property if the object type you use to set that property can be created by processing a string.","pos":[22169,22307]},{"content":"For primitives, this is always the case, the type conversion is built in to the parser.","pos":[22308,22395]},{"content":"However, certain other object types can also be created by using a string specified as an attribute value, rather than an object element within a property element.","pos":[22396,22559]},{"content":"For this to work, there has to be an underlying type conversion, supported either by that particular property or supported generally for all values that use that 